{#
  Example 03 — Multiple selects in one page.

  Each control gets a distinct `name`. The `name` plays three roles:
    1. It is the hidden input's `name` attribute, so the two
       controls don't share state in an enclosing form.
    2. It is the discriminator on the managed <link> element, so
       each control swaps its own stylesheet without stepping on the
       other.
    3. It seeds the default id prefix ("theme-chooser-{name}"), so
       distinct names also give the two listboxes distinct ids.

  That third role matters: Nunjucks macros cannot generate
  per-instance ids, so two controls sharing a `name` would emit
  duplicate listbox and option ids and break aria-controls /
  aria-activedescendant. If you must share a `name`, pass distinct
  `id` values instead.

  This is useful for: a "global" theme + a per-section accent theme;
  preview-vs-live theme A/B; or a settings page that compares two
  themes side-by-side.

  Note: the active `data-theme` attribute on <html> is set by
  whichever control fires last. To make two independent regions, pass
  a per-control `target` via the client.js init opts (see the script
  below).
#}
{% from "../theme-chooser.njk" import themeChooser %}

<section class="region region-a">
    <h2>Region A</h2>
    {{ themeChooser({
        label: "Region A theme",
        name: "region-a",
        themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
        themes: ["light", "dark"]
    }) }}
</section>

<section class="region region-b">
    <h2>Region B</h2>
    {{ themeChooser({
        label: "Region B theme",
        name: "region-b",
        themesUrl: "/assets/themes/",
        themes: ["abyss", "cupcake", "dracula"]
    }) }}
</section>

<script type="module">
    import { initThemeChooser } from "../theme-chooser.client.js";

    const a = document.querySelector(
        "[data-lily-theme-chooser-root][data-lily-theme-chooser-name='region-a']",
    );
    const b = document.querySelector(
        "[data-lily-theme-chooser-root][data-lily-theme-chooser-name='region-b']",
    );
    if (a) initThemeChooser(a, { target: a.closest("section.region-a") });
    if (b) initThemeChooser(b, { target: b.closest("section.region-b") });
</script>
